│ Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe issue is an assertion failure in            │
│ `ScheduleData::incrementUnscheduledDeps()` at line 4773, which checks that  │
│ `hasValidDependencies()` returns true before incrementing unscheduled       │
│ dependencies. The debugger shows that both `Dependencies` and               │
│ `UnscheduledDeps` are -1 (equal to `InvalidDeps`), meaning dependency       │
│ information hasn't been calculated yet. This happens when trying to         │
│ decrement unscheduled dependencies for a control dependency during          │
│ scheduling.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n\nFrom the debug log, we can see  │
│ the SLP vectorizer is processing a store chain of 4 stores. It successfully │
│ schedules smaller bundles but fails when trying to schedule the full        │
│ 4-element bundle. The critical part of the log shows:\n\n```\nSLP: try      │
│ schedule bundle [<Copyable>  %call = tail call i32 @f1(i32 %add4),   %add7  │
│ = add i32 %add6, %mul,   %add4 = add i32 %add, 0] in block entry\n...\nSLP: │
│ check for readiness (mem):   %call = tail call i32 @f1(i32 %add4)\nSLP:     │
│ check for readiness (ctrl):   %call = tail call i32 @f1(i32                 │
│ %add4)\n```\n\nThis indicates that the scheduler is processing control      │
│ dependencies for a call instruction that's marked as copyable. The crash    │
│ occurs when trying to decrement unscheduled dependencies for this control   │
│ dependency.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe root cause is in the          │
│ `DecrUnsched` lambda function in `BlockScheduling::schedule()` at line      │
│ 5403. The condition `(IsControl || Data->hasValidDependencies())` allows    │
│ control dependencies to bypass the `hasValidDependencies()` check. However, │
│ for copyable elements or instructions that haven't had their dependencies   │
│ calculated yet, `Data->hasValidDependencies()` returns false, and           │
│ `Data->Dependencies` is still `InvalidDeps` (-1).\n\nWhen `IsControl` is    │
│ true (as it is for control dependencies), the code proceeds to call         │
│ `Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1)`, which asserts because the             │
│ dependencies haven't been initialized. Control dependencies should only be  │
│ processed after dependency information has been properly calculated.\n\nThe │
│ issue specifically occurs with copyable elements that are being treated as  │
│ control dependencies before their dependency information is                 │
│ initialized.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to ensure that     │
│ even for control dependencies, we only process them if they have valid      │
│ dependencies. This means changing the condition in the `DecrUnsched` lambda │
│ from `(IsControl || Data->hasValidDependencies())` to                       │
│ `(Data->hasValidDependencies())`. Control dependencies should be handled    │
│ like any other dependency and require proper initialization first.\n\n5.    │
│ Conclusion:\n\nBy requiring valid dependencies for all dependency types     │
│ (including control dependencies), we prevent the assertion failure and      │
│ ensure that the scheduler only processes instructions that have had their   │
│ dependency information properly calculated. This maintains the invariant    │
│ that `incrementUnscheduledDeps()` is only called on instructions with valid │
│ dependency information."})                                                  │
